docs.abstract: Tapestry, which owns Coach and Kate Spade, had hired a law firm to look into the claim against Jide Zeitlin, one of only five Black chief executives in the Fortune 500.
docs.snippet: Tapestry, which owns Coach and Kate Spade, had hired a law firm to look into the claim against Jide Zeitlin, one of only five Black chief executives in the Fortune 500.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jide Zeitlin, the chief executive of Tapestry and one of only five Black chief executives in the Fortune 500, resigned on Tuesday and later said the unexpected move, less than a year into his tenure, was related to a past relationship. The company’s board had been made aware of a misconduct allegation involving Mr. Zeitlin and hired a law firm to investigate, according to a person familiar with the situation who spoke on the condition of anonymity.

headline.main: Tapestry C.E.O. Resigns, Acknowledging Past Relationship

docs.abstract: This week’s standouts in streaming dance, plus something to get the kids involved and moving.
docs.snippet: This week’s standouts in streaming dance, plus something to get the kids involved and moving.
docs.lead_paragraph: Situated in a Rocky Mountain resort town, the Vail Dance Festival has never been the most easily accessible event. But in this summer of digital or (nearly) nothing, it’s available to all, on YouTube through Aug. 15. Since this year’s four programs are mostly a selection of performances filmed in recent years, they offer a chance to discover what, apart from its alpine setting, has made the festival distinct.

headline.main: The Vail All-Stars, San Francisco Dreaming and Black Lives Matter

docs.abstract: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
docs.snippet: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Sometimes it hurts too much to tell the truth.” That line is spoken by the protagonist of Martha Southgate’s 2005 novel “Third Girl From the Left,” trying to explain why her mother rarely talks about her experience surviving the 1921 Tulsa race massacre in Oklahoma, and it’s a sentiment that reverberates through the character’s family and the rest of the novel and indeed through the whole of American society, which for too long has averted its eyes from the scene of the crime in Tulsa. But there’s reason to hope things are changing on the truth-telling front, as detailed in Scott Ellsworth’s new book about the massacre, “The Ground Breaking,” which is one of our recommended books this week, 100 years after the events it describes.

headline.main: 11 New Books We Recommend This Week
